widgets_values: Use checkpoints that are good at composition and poses and have a style that is easy for the OpenPose Preprocessor to extract poses from.The ore realistic the better geerally

When using an SDXL-based checkpoint, set 1 will be forced. Those are the values that SDXL has been trained on, so they're the best fit for it.

You can freely add new presets. The first 2 numbers in each line are used (1st- width, 2nd - height. You can write anything after that, and anything that isn't a number before and between the two numbers.

To add sets, you need to convert to nodes, copy one of the set nodes and connect it's output to the text list node. If you run out of connections, use a text list concatenate node
Some LoRA characters can work well together in this workflow IF they require trigger words. This will help keep them from influencing each other too much.
Most important here are descriptions of poses, interactions, framing and perspective. Only the Pose image extracted from this will be used later with ControlNet

The selected preset is concatenated in front of the main prompt

When adding new presets, they should be separated by a "#" character
The preset text should begin any number of new lines below. The line with '#' and all subsequent empty lines are removed before combining with the main prompt

Instead of generating an image, you can load one here and pass it into the preprocessor for photos or the pose and overlay inputs that the output of the preprocessor goes to for openpose images.

By setting width you can resize to the loaded image to that width while keeping its proportions.

The original and final size will be outputted on the 'Size info' pin and can be inspected with a 'show text' node.
(it has to be separate from the group node as the field is not displayed if included in a group node)

This workflow achieves increased control over composition, especially in regards to character interaction with fine control over each character by first generating an image with the desired composition, running a ControlNet OpenPose Preprocessor on it to extract the character poses and then generating a new image using the poses from the first one while also setting separate prompts to each character with latent couple.

#############################################################################
 ---------------------------------HOW TO USE---------------------------------
#############################################################################
(You will get a some errors using this workflow, it's just a part of how it works)

A) Pre-generating a pose
 1) Mute groups II and III (right-click -> Set Group Notes to Never)
 2) Generate images focusing on the desired pose

OR

B) Load pose
 1) Mute groups I and III
 2) Connect the 'Image Load and Resize to Width' node into group II as described on note next to it
 3) If the pose wasn't detected properly, go back to step #1
 4) Mute group I, unmute group II
 5) Queue prompt, wait for preprocessor to finish and for picures to appear in Subject nodes
 6) If the pose is 
 7) Repeat for each 'Subject' node: right-click -> Open in MaskEditor -> paint mask (mostly follow the detected pose, not the background image, that is only for orientation)
 8) Unmute group III
 9) Queue prompt


- Sometimes you need to queue and cancel twice to see effects (eg. after drawing masks for the combined preview to update properly)
- when in MaskEditor: scroll resizes the brush and right-click is an eraser
- instead of muting group I, it is enough to mute just the 1st Pass group node with ctrl+m
- for more information on specific parts of the workflow refer to attached notes

Add more subjects if needed by cloning them. It's the simplest to insert in between existing ones.
Bypass (ctrl+b) unneeded subjects if you don't want to delete them outright. If you don't paint a mask on one, you'll get an error

nodes.title: IMPORTANT - Regarding SDXL
widgets_values:
First of all, you need specially trained controlnet models for SDXL. SD1.5 controlnets will NOT work for non SD1.5 checkpoints.

SDXL controlnets also will NOT work with PONY checkpoints. Those also require controlnets of their own and as of writing this there aren't any available.

And lastly, personally when testing this, I got very bad results with SDXL. I've tested multiple models and control loras, and the full models were the only ones that managed to follow the controlnet guidance, but the overall result was still washed-out and burnt. At this point I have no idea why that is, and SD1.5 models work just fine, there weren't any changes since the previous version that would warrant those bad results either. If you somehow figure it out, then PLEASE contact me by leaving a comment on CivitAI. Other than that I'd advise against using XL models outside of group I.

When using SDXL-base checkpoints, the generation process in each pass will be split between 2 KSamplers, with the second one running the refiner. The 'refiner step%' widget controls the % of the set steps done by the refiner. It may be a good idea to increase it (so the refiner does more) in the second pass, especially with low denoising.
Setting seed or cfg in 2nd pass to '0', (for seed, set control_after_generate to fixed) will use the setting from 1st pass.

ControlNet Guidance is only present in the base conditioning for 1st pass and is removed from it before upscaling as it slows down sampling and is no longer necessary since the image is already well developed
